(517, 1, '2013-02-04 16:08:18', '2013-02-04 16:08:18', '&nbsp;\r\n<h1><a href="http://geniusworks.co.za/wp-content/uploads/2013/02/LWIHeader.png"><img class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-455" alt="LWIHeader" src="http://geniusworks.co.za/wp-content/uploads/2013/02/LWIHeader.png" width="650" height="200" /></a></h1>\r\n<h1>At Genius Works we believe the models by which leaders navigate the world are not meeting the complexity they face.</h1>\r\n<h3>Therefore, the need to upgrade their modes of operating must shift to meet a changing world.</h3>\r\nMore than ever, leaders require a set of skills that demand them to navigate, approach and meet the needs of their environment with both laser-like will, commitment and follow-through as well as imagination, empathy, courage and audacity.\r\n\r\nLeaders are required to make educated decisions within an exponentially changing landscape of parameters, pressures and responsibilities. To do this, they must learn to handle ambiguity whilst knowing who they are and continuously discerning what matters most.\r\n\r\n<strong>This is no small feat.</strong>\r\n\r\n<img class="size-medium wp-image-503 alignright" style="border: 0px; margin-top: 3px; margin-bottom: 3px;" alt="Solving complex problems" src="../wp-content/uploads/2013/02/A_B-203x300.png" width="203" height="300" />\r\n\r\nThis year we have set up an exciting leadership learning journey for social change-\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nmakers, change agents and ripple makers to assist them to learn the new literacies of what it takes to lead in a world of ever-increasing complexity, ambiguity and change.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>The program is called "Lead with Imagination".</strong>\r\n\r\nOur aim is to help leaders and social innovators within organisations to learn the new literacies of the tools, paradigms and understandings that are required to Lead with Imagination.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nI wanted to share the exciting line-up that we''ll be rolling out this year;\r\n\r\n<strong>Modules will include:</strong>\r\n<h3><strong>Module 1:Â <span style="color: #00ccff;">How to Eat an Elephant</span></strong></h3>\r\nIntroduction to Innovation and ideation.Â ParticipantsÂ will learn how perception governs the way we deal with problems and how to overcome this challenge. Together, we will explore new methods of solution-making, how to develop the ability to see things with new eyes as well as unpack new applicable models of dealing with challenges. Also, we''ll learn cutting edge techniques gathered straight from the Imagineers at Disney.\r\n\r\n<strong>Cape Town:Â </strong>19<sup>th</sup>Â February Â <strong>Â Johannesburg:</strong>Â 26<sup>th</sup>Â of February\r\n\r\n_ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _\r\n<h3><strong>Module 2:Â <span style="color: #00ccff;">Facilitating Genius</span></strong></h3>\r\nThe Skill and the Art of facilitating and extrapolating genius. How to mobilise and facilitate the genius of teams, groups and communities. How to incite, guide and harvest collective wisdom.Â RecommendedÂ for leaders social innovators and managers.\r\n\r\n<strong>Cape Town:Â </strong>20<sup>thÂ </sup>â€“ 21<sup>st</sup>Â February Â Â <strong>Johannesburg:</strong>Â 27<sup>th</sup>Â â€“ 28<sup>th</sup>Â February\r\n\r\n_ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _\r\n<h3><strong>Module 3:Â <span style="color: #00ccff;">Re-Imagining Systems</span></strong></h3>\r\nTheories,Â techniquesÂ and applications of how to learn to think and act systemically. How to design systemic engagements within organisations and collaboratives. Introduction to Systems Thinking (Part 1) and Places to intervene in a System (Part 2). This revolutionary program teaches individuals the basics of both Biomimicry as a perception and problem solving tool as well as the latest research in systemic interventions.\r\n\r\n<strong>Cape Town:Â </strong>14<sup>th</sup>Â â€“ 16<sup>th</sup>Â MarchÂ  Â <strong>Johannesburg:</strong>Â 11<sup>th</sup>Â â€“ 13<sup>th</sup>Â April<strong></stron